# Job Conventions

## Jobs Are the Async Service Layer

Background work belongs in jobs, not in service objects. A job calls a model
method asynchronously — it is not a place to write domain logic. Jobs fill the
slot where service objects would be tempting for async orchestration; the model
still owns the domain logic. (See **`rules/services.mdc`** — "There Is No
Service Layer" — for where orchestration code does not belong.)

```ruby
# Good — job delegates to the model
class NotifySubscribersJob < ApplicationJob
  queue_as :default

  def perform(article_id)
    article = Article.find(article_id)
    article.notify_subscribers
  end
end

# Bad — domain logic inside perform
class NotifySubscribersJob < ApplicationJob
  def perform(article_id)
    article = Article.find(article_id)
    article.subscribers.each do |subscriber|
      # business rules and mail logic here — belongs on the model
    end
  end
end
```

## Pass IDs, Not Objects

```ruby
# Good — find the record fresh in perform
NotifySubscribersJob.perform_later(article.id)

def perform(article_id)
  article = Article.find(article_id)
  article.notify_subscribers
end
```

## Enqueue After Commit

Never enqueue a job inside an open transaction — the job runs before commit
or after a rollback.

```ruby
# Good — after_commit fires only when the transaction commits
after_create_commit :notify_subscribers_later

private
  def notify_subscribers_later
    NotifySubscribersJob.perform_later(id)
  end
```

## Idempotency

Jobs can be retried. Every `perform` must be safe to run twice.

```ruby
def perform(subscription_id)
  subscription = Subscription.find(subscription_id)
  return if subscription.cancelled?   # guard against duplicate execution
  subscription.cancel
end
```

## Error Handling

```ruby
# Transient errors — retry with backoff
retry_on Net::OpenTimeout, wait: :polynomially_longer, attempts: 5

# Permanent errors — discard without retrying
discard_on ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound
```

## Recurring Jobs — Use Solid Queue's Built-In Scheduler

Solid Queue ships with a cron-style scheduler. Do not reach for `whenever`
or any other scheduling gem — that is not omakase.

Define recurring tasks in `config/recurring.yml` (a separate flat file,
not nested inside `config/queue.yml`):

```yaml
# config/recurring.yml
daily_digest:
  class: DailyDigestJob
  schedule: "0 8 * * *"   # standard cron — every day at 08:00
```

The schedule accepts standard cron syntax or Fugit natural language
(`"every day at 8am"`). Full patterns: **`skills/writing-jobs/references/patterns.md`** § Scheduling.

Canonical patterns: **`skills/writing-jobs/references/patterns.md`**.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| Domain logic in `perform` | Model method; job just calls it |
| Passing ActiveRecord objects as arguments | Pass IDs |
| `perform_now` in production | `perform_later` |
| Enqueueing inside a transaction | `after_commit` callback |
| Wrapping `deliver_later` in a job | Call `deliver_later` directly |
| No idempotency consideration | Guard clause at the top of `perform` |
| Silently rescuing all exceptions | `retry_on` / `discard_on` with specific classes |
| `whenever` or other cron gems for recurring jobs | Solid Queue `recurring_tasks` in `config/solid_queue.yml` |
